{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180918170338|860148318","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Chris_Collins_(American_politician)","to":"Chris Collins (American politician)"}],"pages":{"14122304":{"pageid":14122304,"ns":0,"title":"Chris Collins (American politician)","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-09-18T17:05:43Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n:''For other people named Chris Collins, see [[Chris Collins (disambiguation)|Chris Collins]].''\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Chris Collins\n|image        = Chris Collins official photo.jpg\n|state        = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|district     = {{ushr|NY|27|27th}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2013\n|term_end     = <!-- Leave blank until he is out of office-->\n|predecessor  = [[Brian Higgins]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = 7th [[County Executive|Executive]] of [[Erie County, New York|Erie County]]\n|term_start1  = January 1, 2008\n|term_end1    = December 31, 2011\n|predecessor1 = [[Joel Giambra]]\n|successor1   = [[Mark Poloncarz]]\n|birth_name   = Christopher Carl Collins\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1950|5|20}}\n|birth_place  = [[Schenectady, New York]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|nationality  = American\n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Mary Collins\n|children     = 3\n|education    = [[North Carolina State University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br />[[University of Alabama at Birmingham]] ([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n|website      = {{url|chriscollins.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Christopher Carl Collins''' (born May 20, 1950) is an American politician serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[New York's 27th congressional district]] since 2013. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], he previously was the [[county executive]] of [[Erie County, New York]] from 2007 to 2011. He is a resident of [[Clarence, New York]].<ref name=votesmart>{{cite web|title=Representative Chris Collins's Biography|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/139770/chris-collins#.UNx4jHf4Igo|work=Vote Smart|accessdate=November 14, 2012}}</ref> \n\nCollins was the first sitting U.S. Representative to endorse [[Donald Trump]] for [[President of the United States]]<ref name=\"buffalonews1\">Zremski, Jerry. \"[http://www.buffalonews.com/city-region/washington-politics/chris-collins-becomes-first-sitting-member-of-congress-to-endorse-trump-20160224 Chris Collins becomes first sitting member of Congress to endorse Trump]\". ''The Buffalo News''. February 24, 2016.</ref> and he served on the Donald Trump presidential transition team.<ref> WGRZ-TV, [https://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/2016/11/12/rep-chris-collins-named-trump-transition-team/93718068/ \"Rep. Chris Collins named to Trump transition team\"], ''Democrat and Chronicle'', November 16, 2016.</ref> Collins and his son, Cameron, were arrested by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] on August 8, 2018 and charged with [[insider trading]] and [[making false statements]] by the office of U.S. Attorney [[Geoffrey Berman]].<ref>Erica Ordin and Maegan Vazquez. [https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/08/politics/chris-collins-indicted-insider-trading/index.html \"New York Republican Rep. Chris Collins indicted on insider trading charges\"], ''CNN'', August 8, 2018.</ref> The [[Securities Exchange Commission]] filed concurrent civil charges against Collins. Three days later, Collins announced he was suspending his bid for a fourth term.<ref name=suspend>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/11/politics/chris-collins-suspends-campaign/index.html|title=Chris Collins suspends re-election campaign following insider trading charges|author1=Meagan Vazquez|author2=Eric Bradner|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> On September 17, 2018, he announced a course reversal and that he would actually seek another term.<ref name=\"NYTimes2018Sep17\">{{cite news |first1=Shane |last1=Goldmacher |first2=Lisa W. |last2=Foderaro |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/17/nyregion/chris-collins-congress-election-campaign.html?rref=collection%2Fsectioncollection%2Fnyregion&action=click&contentCollection=nyregion&region=rank&module=package&version=highlights&contentPlacement=2&pgtype=sectionfront |title=Reversing Course, Chris Collins Will Seek 4th House Term Despite Indictment |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and business career==\nCollins was born in 1950 in [[Schenectady, New York]], the son of Constance (Messier) and Gerald Edward Collins.<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=rzUXAQAAMAAJ&q=%22COLLINS,+CHRISTOPHER+CARL%22&dq=%22COLLINS,+CHRISTOPHER+CARL%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiPrrGVr9_cAhVkw4MKHR6vBksQ6AEILjAG]</ref> Collins moved around the country with his family as his father was transferred several times by [[General Electric]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/democratandchronicle/obituary.aspx?n=gerald-e-collins&pid=138346552#fbLoggedOut|title=Gerald E. \"Jerry\" Collins obituary |publisher=Legacy.com |date=January 8, 2010|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nCollins graduated from [[Hendersonville High School (North Carolina)|Hendersonville High School]] in [[Hendersonville, North Carolina]], in 1968.<ref>{{cite web|last=Axtell|first=Nathaniel |url=http://www.blueridgenow.com/article/20121113/ARTICLES/121119929|title=Congressman-elect Chris Collins of New York is a 1968 graduate of Hendersonville High School |publisher=BlueRidgeNow.com|date=November 13, 2012|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref> \n\nHe earned a Bachelor of Science in Mechanical Engineering from [[North Carolina State University]] in 1972 where he was a member of [[Sigma Pi]] fraternity.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=Spring 1980 |volume=68|number=1|magazine=The Emerald of Sigma Pi|title=Alumni Keep Active |pages=7 |url=http://www.enivation.com/SigmaPi/archive/Emerald/1980/SP_EMERALD_VOL_68_NO_1_SPRING_1980.pdf}}</ref> Collins was inducted into the North Carolina State University Mechanical and Aerospace Engineering Department Hall of Fame in November 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mae.ncsu.edu/news/article/28836/congratulations-to-the-2015-mae-hall|title=Congratulations to the 2015 MAE Hall of Fame Inductees|date=November 19, 2015|publisher=North Carolina State University|accessdate=January 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105013239/http://www.mae.ncsu.edu/news/article/28836/congratulations-to-the-2015-mae-hall/|archive-date=January 5, 2016|dead-url=yes}}</ref> He then earned an MBA from the [[University of Alabama at Birmingham]] in 1975.<ref name=votesmart/>\n\nCollins spent years in the business world.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} As an entrepreneur he was the President and CEO of Nuttall Gear Corporation located in [[Niagara Falls, New York]].<ref name=votesmart/> Nuttall Gear was a 1983 leveraged buyout of the [[Westinghouse Electric]] Gear Division located in Buffalo, New York.<ref name=\"nuttallgear1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nuttallgear.com/nuttall-history.asp|title=History |publisher=Nuttall Gear|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref> Collins sold Nuttall in 1997 to [[Colfax Corporation]], based in [[Annapolis, Maryland]].<ref name=\"nuttallgear1\"/>\n\nAfter losing a race for Congress in 1998, Collins purchased or invested in over twenty bankrupt and financially troubled companies.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} These companies were combined into several platform companies.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} His current companies include: [[Innate Immunotherapeutics]],<ref>Thomas, Kate, [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/13/health/innate-immunotherapeutics-tom-price.html \"Australian Drug Maker Has Low Profile but Powerful Backers in Washington\"], ''The New York Times'', January 13, 2017; retrieved January 15, 2017.</ref> Mead Supply, Oxygen Generating Systems Intl., Audubon Machinery Corp, Schlyer Machine, Volland Electric and ZeptoMetrix Corporation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070923/CITYANDREGION/309239978|title=Private sector savvy Can Chris Collins' business expertise save Erie County?|publisher=''The Buffalo News''|date=September 23, 2007|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\n\n===1998 congressional election===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections, 1998}}\nCollins challenged 24-year incumbent Democratic U.S. Congressman [[John J. LaFalce]] in [[New York's 29th congressional district]]. During the campaign, Collins was one of the first congressional candidates to call for President [[Bill Clinton]]'s resignation in the wake of the [[Monica Lewinsky scandal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BN&p_theme=bn&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF9B384F4CD4E4&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=News Archives: The Buffalo News|publisher=Nl.newsbank.com|date=October 29, 1998|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nLaFalce touted his own record of [[Earmark (politics)|bringing home the bacon]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BN&p_theme=bn&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF9B38D85DAEE6&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=News Archives: The Buffalo News|publisher=Nl.newsbank.com|date=October 30, 1998|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref> and was re-elected by 58% to 41%.\n\n===Erie County Executive===\n{{POV section|date=August 2018}}\n====Elections====\nCollins ran for Erie County Executive in 2007 on the platform of smaller county government, lower taxes and [[Six Sigma]].<ref name=polarbear/> His campaign slogan was \"Elect a Chief Executive, not a Chief Politician.\" Collins defeated Democrat James P. Keane, the deputy county executive of the [[Dennis Gorski]] administration, with 63% in what was considered an \"upset\" win.<ref name=defeated/>\n\nOn November 8, 2011, Collins lost his bid for re-election, a race he was predicted to win.<ref name=considering/> He was defeated by Democratic candidate [[Mark Poloncarz]], the Erie County Comptroller.<ref>{{cite news|title=Poloncarz Wins Erie County Executive Race|first=Athan|last=Kompos|url=http://www.wgrz.com/news/article/141103/37/Collins-Conceeds-to-Poloncarz-in-Erie-County-Executive-Race|work=[[WGRZ]]|accessdate=November 14, 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130210103016/http://www.wgrz.com/news/article/141103/37/Collins-Conceeds-to-Poloncarz-in-Erie-County-Executive-Race|archive-date=February 10, 2013|dead-url=yes}}</ref>\n\nIn a county with 140,000 more Democrats than Republicans, Collins won 39 of the 44 municipalities.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} Poloncarz won the 5 remaining municipalities, including the City of [[Buffalo, NY|Buffalo]], by a margin of 81% to 19%.<ref name=considering>{{cite news|title=Chris Collins Considering Getting Back Into Politics|first=Dave|last=McKinley|url=http://www.wgrz.com/news/article/149180/37/Collins-Considering-Getting-Back-Into-Politics|work=[[WGRZ]]|date=January 9, 2012|accessdate=April 18, 2013|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130209040704/http://www.wgrz.com/news/article/149180/37/Collins-Considering-Getting-Back-Into-Politics|archive-date=February 9, 2013|dead-url=yes}}</ref>\n\n====Tenure====\n[[File:Chris Collins speaks at the 2008 RNC (3).jpg|thumb|Collins speaking at the [[2008 Republican National Convention]]]]\nWhen Collins became the county executive, he inherited from his Republican predecessor, Joel Giambra, a nearly bankrupt county that had state-imposed fiscal control with a budget of $1.2 billion.<ref name=polarbear/><ref name=defeated/>\nCollins spoke for three minutes at the [[2008 Republican National Convention]] on September 3, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080904/CITYANDREGION/309049954|title=Collins uses three minutes in spotlight to cover a lot of political ground|publisher=''The Buffalo News''|date=September 4, 2008|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref> He was the only county executive in the country given the opportunity to speak at the RNC.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nCollins reduced overall county debt by over $120 million and created a cash surplus in excess of $100 million.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.erie.gov/exec/pdfs/2012%20EC%20Message.pdf |format=PDF |title=Erie County Budget 2012|publisher=Erie.gov |accessdate=February 25, 2015}}</ref> He reduced county employment by over 1,200 employees (22%)<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/> and fully paid Erie County's state-imposed pension costs without borrowing.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/> Collins reverted the state imposed Fiscal Control Authority to advisory status in 18 months<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090603/CITYANDREGION/306039994 |title=Control board shifts to advisory status while warning that it 'will not go away'|publisher=''The Buffalo News''|date=June 3, 2009|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref> and received approval of a Four Year Financial Plan (2012\u201315) that further reduced county debt by another $100 million.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/> Collins reopened every bridge, road, park and beach that had been closed under previous administration, including rebuilding the historic toboggan runs in Chestnut Ridge Park in Orchard Park.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.buffalonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20100110/CITYANDREGION/301109985|title=Tallyho as tobogganers chase thrill Fun seekers pack Chestnut Ridge Park on Saturday as toboggan chutes open|publisher=''The Buffalo News''|date=January 10, 2010|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs Erie County Executive, Collins recruited a Six Sigma Master Black Belt [explanation needed] from the University at Buffalo who had previously worked as an executive at a Delphi to implement Lean Six Sigma across all county departments under the direction of the county executive to improve efficiency and reduce costs. The position's $115,000 salary plus associated costs was funded by a grant of taxpayer money from the Erie County Control Board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/stories/2007/12/17/daily49.html|title=New, old faces form Collins' team |publisher=Bizjournals.com |date=December 21, 2007|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe laid off almost 1,000 workers<ref name=polarbear/> and effectively repealed the county's Apprenticeship Law.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/stories/2009/02/02/daily44.html|title=Collins has plan to lift Erie County|publisher=Bizjournals.com|date=February 5, 2009|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref> Collins sued the county so that he could unilaterally increase the county attorney's salary by more the $50,000 that was then the amount authorized by the County Legislature.<ref>{{cite news |last=Spina |first=Matthew|title=Judge orders higher pay for county lawyer|url=http://www2.erie.gov/comptroller/sites/www2.erie.gov.comptroller/files/uploads/pdfs/4-5-11%20Buffalo%20News%20Judge%20orders%20higher%20pay%20for%20county%20lawyer.pdf|accessdate=March 19, 2013|newspaper=The Buffalo News|date=April 5, 2011}}</ref> The State Supreme Court Judge presiding over the case ruled in favor of Collins and awarded the higher salary to the incoming County Attorney.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.erie.gov/comptroller/sites/www2.erie.gov.comptroller/files/uploads/pdfs/4-5-11%20Buffalo%20News%20Judge%20orders%20higher%20pay%20for%20county%20lawyer.pdf|format=PDF|title=Judge orders higher pay for county lawyer|publisher=Erie.gov|accessdate=February 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nCollins was sued by the [[United States Department of Justice]] for repeated [[civil rights]] violations of prisoners held in county facilities, including juveniles and prisoners with developmental disabilities.<ref>{{cite web|last=United States Department of Justice|title=Justice Department Files Lawsuit Challenging Conditions at Two Erie County, New York, Correctional Facilities |url=http://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/2009/September/09-crt-1053.html|accessdate=March 15, 2013}}</ref> The Department of Justice and Erie County co-signed a stipulated settlement of dismissal in August 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20110818/CITYANDREGION/308189916|title=U.S. suit on county jail, prison to be dismissed; Justice Department, county attorney sign agreement to end legal action, Collins says|publisher=''The Buffalo News''|date=August 18, 2011|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe was sued by the County Legislature for refusing to issue payments to Erie Community College which had been included in the County's budget.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sampson|first=Doug|title=Erie County Legislature sues County Executive Chris Collins|url=http://buffalo.ynn.com/content/top_stories/523335/erie-county-legislature-sues-county-executive-chris-collins/|accessdate=March 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs County Executive, Collins created the Brighter Future Fund, donating his county salary to local non-profit organizations for the first 18 months of his tenure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/stories/2008/02/04/daily32.html|title=Top county salaries create 'Bright Future'|publisher=Bizjournals.com|date=February 6, 2008|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2008, Erie County experienced a potential Hepatitis A emergency when an infected employee handled produce at a popular supermarket. Over the course of several days, the County vaccinated and inoculated 10,000 people to protect the public. The event was one of the largest vaccination events in the history of the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://buffalonews.com/2008/02/14/hepatitis-scare-raises-concerns-offers-glimpse-into-nightmare-of-a-flu-pandemic/|title=Hepatitis scare raises concerns Offers glimpse into nightmare of a flu pandemic|date=February 14, 2008|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOne year later, Continental Flight 3407 crashed in a residential neighborhood, killing all 49 passengers on board and one person on the ground in Clarence Center. Collins declared a State of Emergency. Collins worked to ensure the cooperation of Erie County departments and other government agencies in the recovery, investigation and family support efforts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/stories/2009/02/23/story7.html|title=Collins reacted 'on instinct' to crash|publisher=Bizjournals.com|date=February 23, 2009|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2009, southern Erie County \u2013 especially the Village of Gowanda \u2013 was devastated by flooding. Dozens of homeowners lost the contents of their basements and first floors. Collins mobilized the County's Emergency Services and Public Works departments to assist local governments in their recovery efforts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090811/CITYANDREGION/308119996|title=Creek Goes on Rampage: Torrential rains cause Cattaraugus Creek to flood, leaving 2 dead, roads awash, Gowanda inundated|publisher=''The Buffalo News''|date=August 11, 2009|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring his [[Lame duck (politics)|lame duck]] period as Chief Executive, Collins proposed spending $6m to upgrade housing for [[polar bear]]s at [[Buffalo Zoo]] at the same time as laying off 155 workers.<ref name=polarbear>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/16/chris-collins-erie-county-polar-bear-housing-layoffs_n_1097326.html|title=Chris Collins, Erie County Executive, Proposes Polar Bear Housing Amid Layoffs|first=John|last=Celock|work=The Huffington Post|date=November 16, 2011|accessdate=April 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Political future====\nBeginning in 2009, Collins was mentioned as a potential candidate for [[Governor of New York]] in the [[New York gubernatorial election, 2010|2010 election]], particularly if [[Rudy Giuliani]] decided not to run.<ref>Dicker, Fred (May 18, 2009). [http://www.nypost.com/seven/05182009/news/columnists/bizman_pol_is_gopers_plan_b_169868.htm BIZMAN POL IS GOPERS' PLAN B], ''New York Post''; retrieved May 19, 2009.</ref><ref name=\"jv0529\">{{cite web |url=http://www.politickerny.com/3787/collins-lazio-up-front-conservative-party-dinner |title=Archived copy |accessdate=July 26, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090907080640/http://www.politickerny.com/3787/collins-lazio-up-front-conservative-party-dinner |archivedate=September 7, 2009 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"wben1009\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wben.com/Is-Chris-Collins-Running-For-Governor-/5374941 |title=* - WBEN NewsRadio 930 : Buffalo & Niagara Falls, NY |website=Web.archive.org |date= |accessdate=July 26, 2017 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718010217/http://www.wben.com/Is-Chris-Collins-Running-For-Governor-/5374941 |archivedate=July 18, 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\nCollins had indicated he would make his decision in January 2010, but observers believed he was strongly leaning toward running.<ref name=\"wgrz121709\">Saykin, Aaron (December 17, 2009). [http://www.wgrz.com/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=72883&catid=37 Chris Collins Slams Rick Lazio As He Readies For NY Governor's Race]. [[WGRZ]]. Retrieved December 17, 2009.</ref> After further pondering, Collins decided not to run on January 26, 2010. He cited a desire to focus on his current job and a lack of fundraising support from downstate donors, which he dubbed the \"status quo.\" He did not endorse [[Rick Lazio]] and encouraged the state party to find someone else, either from the business field or possibly cross-endorsing Democrat [[Steve Levy (politician)|Steve Levy]].<ref name=ends>McCarthy, Robert (January 26, 2010). [http://www.buffalonews.com/home/story/936045.html Collins ends run for governor]. ''[[The Buffalo News]]''; retrieved January 25, 2010.</ref>\n\nBefore his re-election defeat, Collins was mentioned as a potential candidate in the [[New York gubernatorial election, 2014|2014 gubernatorial election]].<ref name=defeated>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/09/chris-collins-andrew-cuomo-erie-county_n_1084960.html|title=Chris Collins, Potential Andrew Cuomo Opponent, Defeated In Reelection Bid |first=John |last=Celock|work=The Huffington Post|date=November 9, 2011|accessdate=April 18, 2013}}</ref> After his election to Congress, Collins was again mentioned as a possible gubernatorial candidate. In January 2013, he said that he had \"no intention or interest in running for governor in 2014\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://capitaltonightny.ynn.com/2013/01/collins-run-for-governor-is-off-the-table |work=Capital Tonight|first=Nick|last=Reisman|title='Collins: Run For Governor Is 'Off The Table'|date=January 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter initially endorsing [[Jeb Bush]] in the [[United States presidential election, 2016|2016 presidential election]] and donating money to a Bush-aligned [[SuperPAC]], Collins endorsed [[Donald Trump]] when Bush dropped out of the race, becoming the first sitting US representative to do so.<ref>Zremski, Jerry, [http://politicsnow.buffalonews.com/2016/08/24/clinton-outraises-trump-eightfold-western-new-york/ \"Clinton outraises Trump eightfold in Western New York\"], ''The Buffalo News'', August 24, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Collins was indicted for insider trading by the Department of Justice.<ref>{{cite web|author=Renae Merle |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2018/08/08/rep-christopher-collins-r-ny-charged-with-insider-trading-federal-prosecutors-announce/?utm_term=.4c80cbd15ea2 |title=Rep. Chris Collins (R-N.Y.) charged with insider trading, federal prosecutors announce |publisher=The Washington Post |date= |accessdate=August 8, 2018}}</ref> On August 8, 2018, Collins, along with his son Cameron, and Stephen Zarsky, the father of Cameron's fiancee, surrendered to the U.S. Attorney\u2019s Office for New York\u2019s Southern District for charges of [[wire fraud]], conspiracy to commit [[securities fraud]], seven counts of securities fraud, and [[Making false statements|lying to the FBI]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/2018/08/08/chris-collins-arrested-insider-trading-fbi-ny-27-trump-supporter/933331002 | title=Rep. Chris Collins indicted on federal securities fraud charges |publisher=Democratandchronicle.com |date= |accessdate=August 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Elections===\n====2012====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in New York, 2012#District 27}}\nAfter losing his County Executive re-election campaign, Collins ruled out a future bid for office. In January 2012, he was reported to be considering running for Congress<ref name=considering/> and on March 25, 2012, Collins announced he was running in New York's newly-drawn [[New York's 27th congressional district|27th Congressional District]]. The district had previously been the 26th District, and had long been a Republican bastion. However, in a 2011 special election, Democratic Erie County Clerk [[Kathy Hochul]] became the first Democrat to represent the district since 1971.\n\nOn June 26, 2012, Collins won the Republican primary, defeating [[Iraq War]] veteran [[David Bellavia]] 60%\u201340%. Collins had the Republican and Conservative party lines for the November general election and defeated Hochul 51%\u201349%,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2012/house/ny/new_york_27th_district_collins_vs_hochul-3347.html|title=Election 2012 \u2013 New York 27th District \u2013 Collins vs. Hochul|publisher=RealClearPolitics|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref> a difference of 4,312 votes.\n\n====2014====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in New York, 2014#District 27}}\nCollins won re-election to a second term by defeating Democratic opponent Jim O'Donnell 72%\u201328%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/election/2014/results/state/NY/house/27|title=New York House results \u2013 2014 Election Center|publisher=CNN.com|accessdate=February 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====2016====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in New York, 2016#District 27}}\nCollins won re-election to a third term by defeating Democratic opponent Diana K. Kastenbaum 220,885 (67.7%) to 107,832 (32.3%).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/new-york-house-district-27-collins-kastenbaum|title=New York U.S. House 27th District Results: Chris Collins Wins|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nCollins officially endorsed [[Donald Trump]] for president on February 24, 2016, becoming the first sitting member of Congress to do so. He cited shared pasts in business and a need for businessmen in the [[White House]] as having influenced his decision.<ref name=\"buffalonews1\"/> On July 18, Collins seconded Trump's nomination at the [[2016 Republican National Convention]].\n\n===Tenure===\n====113th Congress====\nCollins was sworn-in on January 3, 2013. Prior to taking the oath of office, House Republican leadership appointed him to serve on both the Agriculture and Small Business committees in the 113th Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wbta1490.com/LocalNews/tabid/115/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/3048/Congressman-elect-Chris-Collins-Receives-Committee-Assignments.aspx |title=Congressman-elect Chris Collins Receives Committee Assignments > WBTA AM 1490 Batavia, New York|publisher=Wbta1490.com|date=December 14, 2012|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref> Soon after taking office, House Small Business Committee Chairman [[Sam Graves]] tapped Collins to chair the subcommittee on Healthcare and Technology.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.buffalonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20130107/CITYANDREGION/130109436|title=Collins gains rare rookie honor as subcommittee chief|publisher=''The Buffalo News''|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, 2014, Collins chaired a field hearing, titled ''Expanding Broadband Access and Capabilities to Small Businesses in Rural New York''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Krencik|first=Jim|title=Telecom reps offer testimony at rural broadband hearing|url=http://thedailynewsonline.com/news/article_4c6ab52e-b0ac-11e3-baa4-001a4bcf887a.html|accessdate=March 31, 2014|newspaper=The Daily News|date=March 21, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325150324/http://thedailynewsonline.com/news/article_4c6ab52e-b0ac-11e3-baa4-001a4bcf887a.html|archive-date=March 25, 2014|dead-url=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Balaban|first=Howard|title=Collins hears broadband testimony|url=http://www.lockportjournal.com/local/x1387878660/Collins-hears-broadband-testimony|accessdate=March 31, 2014|newspaper=Lockport Journal|date=March 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThis field hearing was held at the Orleans County Legislature in [[Albion (village), New York|Albion, New York]], examining access to broadband in rural communities, and the role of the federal government in expanding these capabilities to small businesses.<ref>{{cite news|title=Collins arranges local hearing on broadband issues|url=http://www.journal-register.com/local/x1387869384/Collins-arranges-local-hearing-on-broadband-issues|accessdate=March 31, 2014|newspaper=The Medina Journal Register|date=March 17, 2014}}</ref> Following the field hearing, Collins hosted a roundtable discussion with local community leaders to continue the discussion on the importance of access to broadband in rural communities.<ref>{{cite news|last=Krencik|first=Jim|title=Life in the 'last mile' is ... (buffering)|url=http://thedailynewsonline.com/news/article_fdbeed9e-b0a8-11e3-9a85-001a4bcf887a.html|accessdate=March 31, 2014|newspaper=The Daily News|date=March 21, 2014|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140331221804/http://thedailynewsonline.com/news/article_fdbeed9e-b0a8-11e3-9a85-001a4bcf887a.html|archive-date=March 31, 2014|dead-url=yes}}</ref>\n\nIn announcing his committee assignments, Collins said one of his top goals as a member of Congress would be to work with his colleagues to pass a new Farm Bill.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mpnnow.com/topstories/x1781253499/Collins-talks-to-farmers-in-27th-Congressional-District|title=Collins talks to farmers in 27th Congressional District|publisher=MPNnow.com|date=January 7, 2013|accessdate=September 5, 2013|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130216112937/http://www.mpnnow.com/topstories/x1781253499/Collins-talks-to-farmers-in-27th-Congressional-District|archive-date=February 16, 2013|dead-url=yes}}</ref> On May 15, 2013, Collins voted to approve the 2013 Farm Bill.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thedailynewsonline.com/news/article_87c058ec-bea2-11e2-9e6c-001a4bcf887a.html|title=Farm Bill sent to full House, Senate|publisher=The Daily News Online|accessdate=September 5, 2013|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130905185124/http://thedailynewsonline.com/news/article_87c058ec-bea2-11e2-9e6c-001a4bcf887a.html|archive-date=September 5, 2013|dead-url=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://agriculture.house.gov/press-release/house-ag-committee-approves-farm-bill-significant-savings-reforms|title=House Ag Committee Approves Farm Bill With Significant Savings & Reforms &#124; Committee on Agriculture|publisher=Agriculture.house.gov|accessdate=September 5, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906232636/http://agriculture.house.gov/press-release/house-ag-committee-approves-farm-bill-significant-savings-reforms|archive-date=September 6, 2013|dead-url=yes}}</ref>\n\nSubsequently, on January 29, 2014, Collins voted to approve the Conferenced Farm Bill, known as the Agricultural Act of 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Martin|first=Sloane|title=Farm Bill Passes House |url=http://www.wbta1490.com/LocalNews/tabid/115/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/4768/Farm-Bill-Passes-House.aspx|accessdate=February 10, 2014|newspaper=WBTA AM 1490|date=January 29, 2014}}</ref> President Obama signed the 5 year Agricultural Act of 2014 into law on February 7, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Shear|first=Michael|title=In Signing Farm Bill, Obama Extols Rural Growth|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/08/us/politics/farm-bill.html?_r=0|accessdate=February 10, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFollowing this news, Collins called for the resignation of Secretary of Veterans Affairs [[Eric Shinseki]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wgrz.com/news/article/213967/292/18-Patients-at-Buffalo-VA-Test-Positive-for-Hepatitis-|title=18 Patients at Buffalo VA Test Positive for Hepatitis|publisher=wgrz.com|accessdate=September 5, 2013|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130630145000/http://www.wgrz.com/news/article/213967/292/18-Patients-at-Buffalo-VA-Test-Positive-for-Hepatitis-|archive-date=June 30, 2013|dead-url=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ksdk.com/news/article/379924/28/20-veterans-test-positive-for-hepatits-after-insulin-pens-reused|title=20 veterans test positive for hepatits In Buffalo, N.Y. after insulin pens reused|publisher=ksdk.com|date=May 10, 2013|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn response to a proposal by New York State Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] to provide state prison inmates with a publicly financed college education, Collins introduced the Kids Before Cons Act in February 2014.<ref>Kasperowicz, Pete (February 26, 2014). [http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/government-oversight/199287-should-taxpayers-fund-college-courses-for-inmates \"Should taxpayers fund college courses for prison inmates\"], TheHill.com; accessed May 4, 2017.</ref> The bill would prohibit states from using federal funding for the purpose of providing a college degree to convicted criminals. Collins called the Governor's proposal an insult to law-abiding taxpayers who are struggling to put themselves or their children through college.<ref>''The Livingston County News'' (February 21, 2014) [http://www.thelcn.com/news/collins-joins-state-legislators-in-oppostion-to-cuomo-s-college/article_40c2824a-9ab5-11e3-ac4e-001a4bcf887a.html \"Collins joins state legislators in opposition to Cuomo's 'College for Convicts' Plan\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20140423173928/http://www.thelcn.com/news/collins-joins-state-legislators-in-oppostion-to-cuomo-s-college/article_40c2824a-9ab5-11e3-ac4e-001a4bcf887a.html |date=April 23, 2014 }}, thelcn.com; accessed May 4, 2017.</ref>\n\nCollins' bill allows federal dollars to be used for GED and working training programs in prisons and correctional facilities. Cuomo later abandoned his proposal to use public money to fund his initiative.<ref>Kaplan, Thomas (April 3, 2014). [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/03/nyregion/cuomo-drops-plan-to-use-state-money-to-pay-for-college-classes-for-inmates.html?_r=0 \"Cuomo Drops Plan to Use State Money to Pay for College Classes for Inmates\"], ''The New York Times''; accessed May 4, 2017.</ref>\n[[File:Rep. Chris Collins at Yahoo.jpg|thumb|Collins during a visit to a [[Yahoo]] facility in [[Lockport (city), New York|Lockport, New York]], in 2015]]\n\n;Committee assignments\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Horticulture, Research, Biotechnology, and Foreign Agriculture|Subcommittee on Horticulture, Research, Biotechnology, and Foreign Agriculture]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Small Business|Committee on Small Business]]'''\n** [[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Health and Technology|Subcommittee on Health and Technology]] (Chair)\n** [[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Investigations, Oversight and Regulations|Subcommittee on Investigations, Oversight and Regulations]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Research and Technology|Subcommittee on Research and Technology]]\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Space|Subcommittee on Space]]\n\n====114th Congress====\nIn the 114th Congress, Congressman Collins served on the House Energy and Commerce Committee. He stated his priorities on the Energy and Commerce Committee would be securing American energy independence, ensuring companies at the [[Buffalo Niagara Medical Campus]] receive a fair amount of funding in the competitive grants offered by the [[National Institutes of Health]], continuing oversight of the government's approval for new drugs and medical treatments, and increasing access to broadband Internet service in rural areas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.buffalonews.com/city-region/politics/collins-to-join-influential-house-energy-and-commerce-committee-20141203|title=Collins to join influential House Energy and Commerce Committee|publisher=''The Buffalo News''|date=December 4, 2014|accessdate=January 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n;Committee assignments\n\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Committee on Energy and Commerce]]'''\n**[[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Communications and Technology|Subcommittee on Communications and Technology]]\n**[[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Health|Subcommittee on Health]]\n**[[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n\n====115th Congress====\n\nOn August 8, 2018, following his arrest  by the [[FBI]] for [[Mail and wire fraud|wire fraud]], [[Securities fraud|conspiracy to commit securities fraud]], seven counts of securities fraud, and [[Making false statements|lying to the FBI]],<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Representative Chris Collins (R-NY 27) was stripped of all congressional committee assignments by Speaker of the House [[Paul Ryan]] who also called for the House Ethics Committee to look into the allegations, saying: \u201cInsider trading is a clear violation of the public trust.\u201d<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/08/nyregion/chris-collins-insider-trading.html|title=New York Congressman Chris Collins Is Charged With Insider Trading|access-date=2018-08-08|language=en}}</ref>\n \n;<s>Committee assignments</s>\n\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|<s>Committee on Energy and Commerce</s>]]'''\n**[[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Communications and Technology|<s>Subcommittee on Communications and Technology</s>]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Health|<s>Subcommittee on Health</s>]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|<s>Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations</s>]]\n\n==Political positions==\nAccording to ''[[The New York Times]]'', Collins has been \"one of Donald Trump\u2019s earliest and most ardent supporters\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/01/nyregion/cuomo-independence-line-ballot-governor-election.html|title=Third-Party Line Will Feature Governor Cuomo, and a Slew of Republicans|access-date=August 1, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Law enforcement===\nIn February 2014, Collins introduced the Kids before Cons Act to prohibit the use of federal money to provide college education to convicted criminals in prison. An editorial in ''The New York Times'' said, \"These ridiculous arguments are unmoored from both reason and reality.\" A 2013 RAND study of 30 years of research found that every dollar spent on inmate education saves $4 to $5 on re-incarceration.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/09/opinion/gov-cuomo-drops-the-ball.html \"Gov. Cuomo Drops the Ball\"], ''The New York Times'', April 8, 2014.</ref>\n\nCollins supported Donald Trump's May 9, 2017, firing of FBI Director [[James Comey]], saying \"The Director of the FBI serves at the pleasure of the President. I respect President Trump's decision at the recommendation of the Attorney General.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://13wham.com/news/top-stories/leaders-react-to-comey-firing|title=Congressional representatives from Rochester area react to Comey firing|website=13wham.org|access-date=May 10, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Health care===\nOn May 4, 2017, Collins voted in favor of repealing the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare) and to pass the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act]].<ref name=\":02\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/ahca-house-vote/|title=How the House voted to pass the GOP health-care bill|website=Washington Post |accessdate=May 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/04/politics/house-health-care-vote/index.html|title=How every member voted on health care bill |last=Staff |first=C.N.N.|website=CNN|access-date=May 4, 2017}}</ref> Collins made headlines for admitting he had not read the full health care bill before voting.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Manduley |first1=Christina|title=Congressman admits he didn't read full health care bill before voting|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/04/politics/chris-collins-gop-health-care-bill-cnntv |website=CNN |publisher=Turner Broadcasting System, Inc.|accessdate=May 5, 2017}}</ref> In an interview with a ''Buffalo News'' reporter, Collins admitted that he was unaware but unconcerned that New York would lose $3 billion worth of federal funds annually under the AHCA, by losing New York's Essential Health Plan, an optional ACA program that provided low-cost health insurance to thousands of \"low- and middle-income people who d[id]n't qualify for Medicaid\", to which Collins responded, \"No. [I was not aware] But it doesn't surprise me for you to tell me that there were two states in the nation that were taking advantage of some other waiver program and New York was one of the two states.\"<ref name=\"buffalonews_AHCA_2017\">{{cite web |url=http://buffalonews.com/2017/05/04/collins-says-didnt-read-health-bill-proves|title=Watch: Chris Collins admits he didn't read health care bill|author=Jerry Zremski|date=May 4, 2017 |accessdate=May 5, 2017|work=The Buffalo News}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview in ''The Batavian'' on June 24, 2012, Collins said: \"People now don't die from prostate cancer, breast cancer and some of the other things. The fact of the matter is, our healthcare today is so much better, we're living so much longer, because of innovations in drug development, surgical procedures, stents, implantable cardiac defibrillators, neural stimulators \u2013 they didn't exist 10 years ago.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Chris Collins wants to go to Washington to restore the American Dream |first=Howard |last=Owens |url=http://thebatavian.com/howard-owens/chris-collins-wants-go-washington-restore-american-dream/32549|newspaper=The Batavian|date=June 24, 2012|accessdate=November 14, 2012}}</ref> In response, Elise Foley of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' wrote, \"An estimated 577,190 people in the United States will die from cancer this year, including about 39,920 deaths from breast cancer and 28,170 from prostate cancer\", citing data from the [[American Cancer Society]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Chris Collins: 'People Now Don't Die From Prostate Cancer, Breast Cancer' |first=Elise |last=Foley |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/03/chris-collins-cancer_n_1647196.html|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=July 3, 2012|accessdate=November 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Artvoice]] wrote, \"The implantable cardiac defibrillator and neural stimulators, or TENS devices, were both invented and patented in the late 60s or early 70s; therefore, they existed '10 years ago'\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.artvoice.com/avdaily/2012/07/03/collins-people-dont-die-from-prostate-breast-cancers-anymore|title=Collins: People Don't Die from Prostate, Breast Cancers Anymore|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Taxes===\nCollins was one of only two House members from New York state (along with [[Tom Reed (politician)|Tom Reed]]) to support the provision in Republican tax overhaul bill introduced November 2, 2017, eliminating personal deductions for state income taxes on federal tax forms.  In response  New York Governor  [[Andrew Cuomo]] labeled the two lawmakers \"the Benedict Arnolds of their time\", claiming that the loss of the deduction would cost New York State taxpayers nearly $15 billion and do grave damage to the state.<ref>Jerry Zremski [http://buffalonews.com/2017/10/31/reed-collins-revel-in-tax-compromise-that-cuomo-schumer-abhor/ \"Reed and Collins revel in tax compromise that Cuomo and Schumer abhor\"], ''Buffalo News'', November 1, 2017, Retrieved November 4, 2017</ref> In a Twitter post cited by Fox Business News, Collins claimed that the House Republican tax reform legislation would provide a reduction in taxes to 95% or more of the individuals in his district.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/FoxBusiness/status/929136626332086274/video/1|title=.@RepChrisCollins: \"95% or more of our constituents... are going to pay less next year, they're going to see that in their paychecks.\"pic.twitter.com/KxEP2jmNE6|last=Business|first=F. O. X.|date=<!--4:00 PM - -->November 10, 2017|website=@FoxBusiness|language=en|access-date=November 11, 2017}}</ref>  Collins said that under Cuomo, New York is the highest-taxed, most regulated, least business-friendly state in the nation and urged Cuomo to cut the state's budget.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2017/10/29/to-king-cuomo-cutting-new-yorkers-taxes-is-treason/|title=To 'King Cuomo,' cutting New Yorkers' taxes is treason|date=October 30, 2017|work=New York Post|access-date=November 11, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> Asked if his donors were pleased with the House's tax reform plan so far, Collins said, \"My donors are basically saying 'get it done or don't ever call me again.'\"<ref>{{cite news|title=GOP lawmaker: Donors are pushing me to get tax reform done|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/359110-gop-lawmaker-donors-are-pushing-me-to-get-tax-reform-done|author=Marcos, Christina|date=November 7, 2017|publisher=''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]''|access-date=November 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===National security===\nCollins supported President Donald Trump's 2017 [[Executive Order 13769]] restricting immigration from seven Muslim-majority countries. He stated that \"I get a little frustrated with the folks who don't like Trump trying to make something into something it's not. So I'm just disappointed that we can't have a true and honest debate without someone inflaming the situation and claiming there's religious overtones.\"<ref name=\"Blake1\">{{cite web|last1=Blake|first1=Aaron|title=Coffman, Gardner join Republicans against President Trump's travel ban; here's where the rest stand|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2017/01/29/republicans-on-trump-travel-ban|website=Denver Post|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn October 2009, Collins compared [[Sheldon Silver]], who is Jewish, to [[Adolf Hitler]], [[Napoleon]], and the [[antichrist]]. Collins later apologized for his comments.<ref>{{cite news|title=Erie County Executive Collins regrets comparing Sheldon Silver to Hitler, anti-Christ|first=Elizabeth|last=Benjamin|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2009-10-26/news/17935078_1_gubernatorial-bid-governor-and-legislative-leaders-anti|newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|date=October 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2010, two Republican assemblymen, including Assemblyman Joseph Errigo, claimed that at Gov. David Paterson's crowded State-of-the State address, Collins told a woman that: \"I'm sure if you offer someone a lap dance you can find a place to sit.\"<ref>\"The Daily Politics\", [http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/collins-foot-in-mouth-disease-blog-entry-1.1676654 \"Collins' Foot-In-Mouth Disease?\"], ''[[New York Daily News]]'', December 18, 2010; retrieved January 15, 2017.</ref> Collins denied making the comment, and claimed that there was a \"political smear campaign\" going on against him.<ref>Zremski, Jerry, [http://buffalonews.com/2012/06/23/bellavia-attacks-collins-controls-google-search \"Bellavia attacks Collins, controls Google search\"], ''The Buffalo News'', June 23, 2012; retrieved January 15, 2017.</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Buckley |first=Eileen |url=http://news.wbfo.org/post/collins-accuses-albany-insiders-political-smear-campaign |title=Collins accuses Albany insiders of political smear campaign &#124; WBFO |publisher=News.wbfo.org |date=January 21, 2010 |accessdate=August 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn November 28, 2016, Collins described [[Mitt Romney]], who was being considered by President-elect Donald Trump for his Secretary of State, as a \"self-serving egomaniac\". On the TV show ''New Day'', Collins told host [[Chris Cuomo]], \"What do I know about Mitt Romney? I know that he's a self-serving egomaniac who puts himself first, who has a chip on his shoulder, and thinks that he should be president of the United States.\"<ref>Wright, David, [http://www.cnn.com/2016/11/28/politics/romney-secretary-of-state-criticism/index.html \"Trump ally: Romney a 'self-serving egomaniac'\"], [[CNN]], November 28, 2016.</ref>\n\nOn February 10, 2017, Collins told Chris Cuomo on [[CNN]]'s ''New Day'' that elected officials should not have to release their tax history. This comment came in response to the ongoing controversy surrounding President Trump's refusal to release his tax forms. Collins told Cuomo \"I've always said he shouldn't report his taxes. I don't think any elected official should\".<ref>Scott, Eugene, [http://www.cnn.com/2017/02/10/politics/chris-collins-donald-trump-taxes-cnntv \"Congressman: Elected officials shouldn't release taxes\"], [[CNN]], February 10, 2017.</ref>\n\nFollowing a June 14, 2017, shooting during a GOP baseball practice for an annual Washington, DC charity game that pits Democrats versus Republicans, Collins blamed Democrats, stating that \"I can only hope that the Democrats do tone down the rhetoric. The rhetoric has been outrageous in the anger directed at Donald Trump.\"<ref>[http://www.cbsnews.com/news/republicans-democrats-call-for-unity-after-congressional-shooting-alexandria/ \"Republicans, Democrats call for unity after congressional shooting\"], CBS News, June 14, 2017; retrieved June 17, 2017</ref> Shortly after making that comment, Collins noted that it is important for everyone, including himself, to tone down partisan rhetoric and \"recognize that we are all one country and all proud Americans.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://chriscollins.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/congressman-chris-collins-statement-on-shooting-in-alexandria-virginia|title=Congressman Chris Collins Statement on Shooting in Alexandria, Virginia|date=June 14, 2017|work=Congressman Chris Collins|access-date=June 18, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Collins also vowed to start carrying a gun with him \"from this day forward.\"<ref>Jenkins, Aric, [http://time.com/4818560/chris-collins-steve-scalise-shooting/ \"GOP Congressman Vows to Carry Gun 'From This Day Forward' Following Virginia Shooting\"], ''Time'', June 14, 2017, Retrieved June 17, 2017</ref>\n\n==Indictment and arrest for insider trading ==\n\n=== Background ===\nIn August 2016 Collins purchased 4 million more shares in Innate Immunotherapeutics, making him the largest shareholder at that time.  At the same time, [[Tom Price (American politician)|Tom Price]], \na then-Republican Congressman who later served as [[United States Secretary of Health and Human Services]] under [[Donald Trump]], purchased 400,613 Innate Immunotherapeutics shares valued at $100,000 to $250,000.<ref name=\"NYT_Thomas_Washington_backers\">{{citation|title=Australian Drug Maker Has Low Profile but Powerful Backers in Washington|date=January 24, 2017|url=https://nyti.ms/2jCTsc3|author=Katie Thomas|publisher=''The New York Times''|accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref> Senator [[Ron Wyden]] (D-Oregon) raised potential concerns about Price's Innate Immunotherapeutics investments which \"could be affected by legislation that comes before Congress.\"<ref name=\"NYT_Thomas_Washington_backers\" /> Innate Immunotherapeutics acquired Amplia Therapeutics in April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.innateimmuno.com/irm/PDF/1467_0/AcquisitionofAmpliaTherapeuticsQuestionsandAnswers|title=Innate Immunotherapeutics proposed acquisition of Amplia Therapeutics \u2013 Questions & Answers|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Collins is no longer a director of Innate Immunotherapeutics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.innateimmuno.com/irm/PDF/1469_0/ResultsofMeeting|title=Results of General Meeting|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, White House ethics investigators \"began probing Collins for his role in recruiting investors to buy stock in [[Innate Immunotherapeutics]] after several complaints were filed.\"<ref name=\"thehill_Collins_2017\">{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/336842-exclusive-gop-lawmaker-talked-stocks-with-colleagues|title=Exclusive: GOP lawmaker talked stocks with colleagues|last=Wong|first=Scott|date=June 8, 2017|access-date=June 8, 2017|quote=\"The Buffalo News reported that many in the [Buffalo]'s business elite had bought stock in the drug company after hearing from Collins ... Collins first invested in Innate Immunotherapeutics, which has developed a drug to fight advanced multiple sclerosis, about 15 years ago. He said he's raised money for the company during tough times and has earned a spot on its board of directors ... [In August 2016, Collins] purchased an additional 4 million shares. On [January 27, 2017,] the stock hit an all-time high of $1.83 per share, but it was trading at 74 cents per share on [May 7, 2017].\"}}</ref>  Members of Congress are explicitly barred from trading stocks using insider information.<ref name=\"thehill_Collins_2017\" /> In October 2017, the [[Office of Congressional Ethics|Office of Congressional Ethics (OCE)]] said they had \"substantial reason\" to believe that Collins had improperly used his public office to benefit Innate, and had forwarded nonpublic information to other investors.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/congressional-ethics-office-says-new-york-republican-may-have-violated-law-1507847729|title=Congressional Ethics Office Says New York Republican May Have Violated Law|last=Tau|first=Byron|date=October 12, 2017|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=October 13, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> The OCE said Collins sent nonpublic information to investors about drug trials and that he visited the [[National Institutes of Health]] to discuss a drug's clinical trial, saying that this violated House ethics rules.<ref name=\"auto\" /> The House Ethics Committee did not appoint a subcommittee to continue investigating Collins' case.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ethics.house.gov/press-release/statement-chairwoman-and-ranking-member-committee-ethics-regarding-representative-3|title=Statement of the Chairwoman and Ranking Member of the Committee on Ethics Regarding Representative Chris Collins {{!}} House Committee on Ethics|website=ethics.house.gov|language=en|access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Sale of shares ===\nOn June 22, 2017, the CEO of Innate Phamarceuticals sent an email to the company's board of directors, including Collins, explaining that an important drug trial for the company had failed.  According to the FBI, Collins had been attending a picnic at the White House and upon seeing the email, immediately phoned his son and instructed him to sell their shares.  According to the allegations, the sale allowed Collins and his family to save around $570,000 in losses.  The shares eventually dropped around 90% on the news.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n=== Arrest ===\nOn August 8, 2018, Collins, his son Cameron, and the father of Cameron\u2019s fianc\u00e9e, Stephen Zarsky, were arrested by the [[FBI]] and charged with [[Mail and wire fraud|wire fraud]], [[Securities fraud|conspiracy to commit securities fraud,]] seven counts of securities fraud, and [[Making false statements|lying to the FBI]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/08/08/gop-congressman-chris-collins-to-be-indicted-on-insider-trading-charge.html |title=New York GOP Rep. Chris Collins arrested on insider trading charges |publisher=Cnbc.com |date= |accessdate=August 8, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |last=Staff |first=Writer |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/08/08/live-stream-rep-chris-collins-arrest-discussed-prosecutors/934774002/ |title=Live stream: Rep. Chris Collins arrest discussed by prosecutors |work=[[USA Today]] |date=2018-08-08 |accessdate=2018-08-08 }}</ref> \n\nLater that day, [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the US House of Representatives]] [[Paul Ryan]] announced that he had removed Collins from his position on the [[House Energy and Commerce Committee]].  He also referred the matter to the [[United States House Committee on Ethics|House Ethics Committee]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/08/08/paul-ryan-boots-chris-collins-from-house-committee-after-indictment.html|title=Paul Ryan boots GOP Rep. Chris Collins from House panel after insider-trading charges|last=Mangan|first=Dan|date=2018-08-08|work=CNBC|access-date=2018-08-08}}</ref>\n\nCollins planned to run for reelection in 2018. However, on August 11, while maintaining his innocence, Collins announced he was suspending his reelection campaign, but he intended to serve out the balance of his term. Under New York election law, he will remain on the ballot for the November election unless he dies, accepts nomination for a separate office or is disqualified. According to CNN, Republican officials are considering nominating him for a town clerk's post, which would clear the way for him to formally remove his name from the ballot.<ref name=suspend/>  He would also be automatically removed from the ballot if he moved his official residence to one of his homes in Florida and the District of Columbia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/08/11/chris-collins-reelection-bid-insider-trading-773514|first1=Kyle|last1=Cheney|first2=Jimmy|last2=Vielkind|title=Rep. Chris Collins, fighting prosecution, seeks to end reelection bid|work=Politico|date=August 11, 2018|accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref> In either case, the eight Republican county chairs in the district would then select a replacement in a vote weighted by county population.<ref name=suspend/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n{{cite news|title=How the House voted to pass the GOP health care bill|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/ahca-house-vote/|accessdate=May 4, 2017|agency=Washington Post}}}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://chriscollins.house.gov/ Congressman Chris Collins] official U.S. House site\n* [http://collinsforcongress.com/ Chris Collins for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_S